Everything looks absolutely perfect. Both application pods are Running, your internal ClusterIP services are live, and your ingress-nginx-controller is tracking with the updated configuration.

Based on your current service output, you can now access both applications securely over HTTPS directly from your Windows web browser.

Your Secure HTTPS URLs for Windows Browser
Since your Ingress Controller exposes TLS traffic via NodePort fallback on port 30517 (mapped from port 443), copy and paste these exact links into your Chrome, Edge, or Firefox browser:

🔒 App 1 (Secure): ```text
https://my-app.com:30517/app1

🔒 App 2 (Secure): ```text
https://my-app.com:30517/app2


⚠️ Quick Reminder on the Browser Warning
When the page loads, your browser will flash a warning saying "Your connection is not private" or NET::ERR_CERT_AUTHORITY_INVALID.

Don't worry, this is exactly what we expect! It means your OpenSSL configuration worked flawlessly. Because it's a self-signed lab certificate, you just need to:

Click Advanced.

Click Proceed to my-app.com (unsafe).

Once you click proceed, the browser will render your messages encrypted over an active TLS layer!





===================================================================
📖 KUBERNETES LAB ROUTING DOCUMENTATION & BACKUP MANIFESTS
===================================================================

Save this as ingress-plain-http.yaml:
-------------------------------------------------------------------
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: app1
  labels:
    env: prod
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      env: prod
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        env: prod
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: my-container-hashicorp-appv1
          image: hashicorp/http-echo
          args:
            - "-text=Hello , Welcome to App1 "
            - "-listen=:80"
          ports:
            - containerPort: 80
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: app1-svc
spec:
  selector:
    env: prod
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 80
---
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: app2
  labels:
    env: prod-v12
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      env: prod-v12
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        env: prod-v12
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: my-container-hashicorp-appv2
          image: hashicorp/http-echo
          args:
            - "-text=Hello, Welcome to App2"
            - "-listen=:80"
          ports:
            - containerPort: 80
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: app2-svc
spec:
  selector:
    env: prod-v12
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 80
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: nginx-ingress
spec:
  ingressClassName: nginx
  rules:
    - host: my-app.com
      http:
        paths:
          - path: /app1
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: app1-svc
                port:
                  number: 80
          - path: /app2
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: app2-svc
                port:
                  number: 80


Manifest 2: With TLS (Encrypted HTTPS Router)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
This manifest includes the exact tls: array section (with the correct space counts) mapping to your my-app-tls-secret. It terminates SSL handshakes securely on your node's port 30517.

Save this as ingress-secure-tls.yaml:
-------------------------------------------------------------------
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: app1
  labels:
    env: prod
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      env: prod
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        env: prod
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: my-container-hashicorp-appv1
          image: hashicorp/http-echo
          args:
            - "-text=Hello , Welcome to App1 "
            - "-listen=:80"
          ports:
            - containerPort: 80
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: app1-svc
spec:
  selector:
    env: prod
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 80
---
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: app2
  labels:
    env: prod-v12
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      env: prod-v12
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        env: prod-v12
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: my-container-hashicorp-appv2
          image: hashicorp/http-echo
          args:
            - "-text=Hello, Welcome to App2"
            - "-listen=:80"
          ports:
            - containerPort: 80
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: app2-svc
spec:
  selector:
    env: prod-v12
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 80
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: nginx-ingress
spec:
  ingressClassName: nginx
  tls:
    - hosts:
        - my-app.com
      secretName: my-app-tls-secret
  rules:
    - host: my-app.com
      http:
        paths:
          - path: /app1
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: app1-svc
                port:
                  number: 80
          - path: /app2
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: app2-svc
                port:
                  number: 80

Quick Switching commands:
-------------------------------------------------------------------
When you want to switch your entire environment back and forth, you don't need to delete anything else. Just apply the target file directly over the existing configuration, and Kubernetes will handle the hot-reload instantly:

To go plain text:  kubectl apply -f ingress-plain-http.yaml
To go secure TLS:  kubectl apply -f ingress-secure-tls.yaml
